          "body": "Proverbs 26:1-12 is the most concentrated collection of fool-imagery in the Hebrew wisdom tradition. The dominant character type is the *kesil* — not the naive simpleton (*peti*) or the morally arrogant scoffer (*letz*) but the thick-headed, dispositionally obstinate fool whose folly is a stable feature of character, not a passing failure. The eleven occurrences of *kesil* in twelve verses establish what the sages considered the most practically dangerous personality type in community life. What makes this gallery remarkable is not any single proverb but the cumulative effect of the simile-chain: snow in summer, a flitting sparrow, a horse's whip, lame legs, a stone in a sling, a thorn in a drunkard's hand, a dog returning to vomit. Each image adds a different dimension — the fool is seasonally wrong (v. 1), morally harmless when undeserved (v. 2), physically ungovernable (v. 3), rhetorically hazardous (vv. 7, 9), institutionally untrustworthy (vv. 6, 10), and chronically recidivist (v. 11). No single proverb could carry all this freight; the chain is necessary."
