          "title": "The sluggard's portrait — motion without progress and the disease of self-assessment",
          "body": "The four-verse sluggard-section (vv. 13-16) is Proverbs' sharpest concentrated portrait of the *atsel*. The satirical precision is striking. In verse 13 the sluggard quotes a lion — a real danger in the ancient Near East — but places it not in the wilderness where lions actually live but in 'the road' and 'the open square,' where the sluggard would have to go to do his work. The excuse is topographically specific and proportionally absurd. Verse 14 gives the most memorable image: the door turning on its hinges — constant motion, change of position, but zero displacement. The sluggard turns in bed as a door turns on its pivot: he is in perpetual motion without going anywhere. Verse 15 escalates the satire to near-comedy: the sluggard has reached the dish (he is hungry enough for that) but is too weary to complete the journey from dish to mouth. Verse 16 delivers the closing verdict that echoes the fool-section's conclusion: the sluggard considers himself wiser than seven men who can give a discreet answer. The connection is deliberate — the fool and the sluggard share the same pathology. Self-assessed wisdom is the common root of both types, and it is precisely what makes both unreachable by normal correction."
