          "body": "The closing verses (26:27-28) provide the chapter's theological anchor. Verse 27 states what Old Testament scholars have called the 'act-consequence nexus' (Klaus Koch's formulation, though the concept predates him): 'He who digs a pit will fall into it, and he who rolls a stone, it will come back on him.' Both consequences follow the shape of the crime — the pit receives its digger, the stone returns to its roller. This is not merely a prudential warning about tactics; it reflects the Hebrew wisdom tradition's conviction that moral order is woven into creation, that evil done against others carries within it the seed of its own return. Proverbs 1:18-19; 28:10; and Psalm 7:15-16 share the same pattern. The New Testament echo is Galatians 6:7 ('whatever a man sows, this he will also reap'). Verse 28 closes with the chapter's hardest claim: 'A lying tongue *hates* those it crushes.' The sage will not allow flattery and falsehood to be categorized as social failures or character weaknesses. They are acts of aggression — the lying tongue and the flattering mouth are instruments of hatred, not symptoms of weakness. The chapter that began with honor misapplied to a fool ends with hatred operating through beautiful speech. Both errors concern the misuse of language in community — and both, the chapter insists, will be exposed."
